<HH> ============= Screen: Introduction ======================== </HH>

<Markdown id="fba2_introduction" when="!@fba2_completion_checkbox.value">
## Introduction

In this module, you will continue helping Annie's roommate with Johnny, the 6-year-old she babysits. The positive reinforcement techniques from last time are partially working, but Johnny still runs away at bedtime.

In this session, you will review and apply several concepts from your coursework on behavior modification. Specifically, you will:

- Identify the **function of behavior** and the four main functions.
- Understand the **ABCs** (Antecedent, Behavior, Consequence) of behavior analysis.
- Develop an **intervention plan** using a Competing Behavior Pathway.
- Use an **AI Assistant** to support learning and problem solving.

Let's begin.
</Markdown>

<HH> ============= Screen: Use AI to define function of behavior ==== </HH>

<Vertical id="fba2_ai_function_def">
<Markdown id="fba2_ai_function_intro">
## What is the Function of a Behavior?

Try to explain what the function of a behavior is, based on what you know or remember from class. Then get AI feedback on your explanation.
</Markdown>

<TextArea id="fba2_ai_function_prompt" rows="2" placeholder="Type your explanation of function of behavior here..." />

<ActionButton id="fba2_ai_function_btn" label="Get AI Feedback" dependsOn="@fba2_ai_function_prompt.value">
<LLMAction id="fba2_ai_function_action" target="fba2_ai_function_response"><![CDATA[
You are a helpful psychology teaching assistant. One of your students has
provided the following attempt to explain what function of behavior is:
]]>
<Ref id="fba2_ref_function_prompt" target="fba2_ai_function_prompt" />
<![CDATA[
If their response is not a good-faith effort to explain what function
of behavior is, reprimand them about that, and stop without mentioning
what the function of a behavior is or what the four main functions are.
Otherwise, let them know what they've gotten right and explain anything
they've missed or misstated, making your goal to explain the concept of
'function of behavior' in behavioral psychology, including the fact that
'function of behavior' refers to the purpose or reason behind why a
behavior occurs -- what the person gains from the behavior -- and
mentioning the four main functions: attention, escape, access to
tangibles/preferred items, and sensory/automatic reinforcement.

Keep your response accessible for undergraduate students.

Output your response in Markdown with bolded paragraph and list headers,
but keep it short -- no more than a few paragraphs.
]]></LLMAction>
<SetFieldAction
    id="fba2_jjs_prompt_init"
    target="jjs_prompt"
    field="value"
    value="You are a helpful psychology teaching assistant. Create a chart showing the four
functions of behavior (attention, escape, access to tangibles, sensory) with examples
of how each relates to positive and negative reinforcement. Use a markdown table format.
Include concrete examples for each combination of function with positive or negative
reinforcement. Leave a cell blank if the function of the behavior is by definition
incompatible with the type of reinforcement, assuming that negative reinforcement is
compatible with removal of unwanted attention but not with access, while escape is
not compatible with positive reinforcement. Highlight the function names in the
function column." />
<SetFieldAction
    id="fba2_abc_diagram_prompt_init"
    target="ABCs_mermaid_diagram"
    field="value"
    value="If the following question is about the ABCs (Antecedent, Behavior, Consequence) model
and functions of behavior, generate ONLY valid Mermaid flowchart code. No explanations,
no markdown, no code fences — output must start with 'flowchart LR' and contain nothing
else besides valid Mermaid syntax.

Create a single diagram with four subgraphs, one per function of behavior. Each subgraph
shows an Antecedent, Behavior, and Consequence connected by arrows, using a concrete
classroom example. Follow this structure:

flowchart LR
  subgraph escape ['Escape — Negative Reinforcement']
    E_A['Antecedent: ...'] --> E_B['Behavior: ...'] --> E_C['Consequence: ...']
  end
  subgraph attention ['Attention — Positive Reinforcement']
    A_A['Antecedent: ...'] --> A_B['Behavior: ...'] --> A_C['Consequence: ...']
  end
  subgraph tangible ['Access/Tangible — Positive Reinforcement']
    T_A['Antecedent: ...'] --> T_B['Behavior: ...'] --> T_C['Consequence: ...']
  end
  subgraph sensory ['Sensory — Automatic Reinforcement']
    S_A['Antecedent: ...'] --> S_B['Behavior: ...'] --> S_C['Consequence: ...']
  end

Rules:
- Output ONLY mermaid code — no other text whatsoever
- Wrap all node labels in double quotes inside square brackets: E_A['label']
- Use underscores in node names (E_A, not E-A)
- Keep each label under 50 characters
- Do NOT use bare colons, parentheses, or special characters outside the double quotes

If the question is not relevant, output only:
flowchart LR
  A['Please ask about ABCs and functions of behavior']" />
</ActionButton>

<LLMFeedback id="fba2_ai_function_response" render="markdown" />

