<HH> ============= Screen: ABC for Johnny ====================== </HH>

<Vertical id="fba2_abc_johnny">
<Markdown id="fba2_abc_johnny_intro">
## Your Turn: Johnny's ABCs

Using the story about Johnny, explain the sequence of **Antecedent**, **Behavior**, and **Consequence** in your own words.

_Recall: Annie's roommate tells Johnny to get into bed, but he runs away from the room laughing whenever "bed" is mentioned. The roommate chases after him and keeps nagging him to go to bed._
</Markdown>

<TextArea id="fba2_abc_johnny_explanation" placeholder="Write your explanation here..." />

<ActionButton id="fba2_abc_johnny_check_btn" label="Check My Understanding" dependsOn="@fba2_abc_johnny_explanation.value">
<LLMAction id="fba2_abc_johnny_check" target="fba2_abc_johnny_feedback"><![CDATA[
A psychology student was asked to identify the ABCs (Antecedent, Behavior, Consequence)
for this scenario: Annie's roommate tells Johnny to get into bed, but he runs away from
the room laughing. The roommate chases after him and keeps nagging him to go to bed.

The correct answer is:
- Antecedent: Roommate tells Johnny to go to bed
- Behavior: Johnny runs out of the room laughing
- Consequence: Roommate chases after him / he avoids going to bed on time

Here is the student's response:
]]>
<Ref id="fba2_ref_abc_johnny" target="fba2_abc_johnny_explanation" />
<![CDATA[
Evaluate whether the student correctly identified each component. Be encouraging but
specific about what they got right and what needs correction. Keep it brief.
]]>

However, DO NOT give students the correct answer in your response.</LLMAction>
</ActionButton>

<LLMFeedback id="fba2_abc_johnny_feedback" render="markdown" />
</Vertical>


<HH> ============= Screen: Johnny's function ==================== </HH>

<Vertical id="fba2_johnny_function">
<MarkupProblem id="fba2_johnny_function_choice" title="Function of Johnny's Behavior"><![CDATA[
## What is the function of Johnny's behavior?

>>Now that you've identified the ABCs of Johnny's bedtime behavior, what is the function of his running out of the room?<<

( ) Access to preferred activity/object
( ) Attention
(x) Escape
( ) Sensory

[explanation]
The function is **escape**. Johnny's running away is maintained by negative reinforcement — he successfully avoids or delays going to bed (the aversive event). The antecedent (being told to go to bed) triggers the behavior (running away), and the consequence (not having to go to bed right away) reinforces it.
[/explanation]
]]></MarkupProblem>
</Vertical>


